<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Clinton pledges to broaden area for free trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton yesterday raised the prospect of a broad free trade
zone in the western hemisphere by putting the whole of Latin America back at
the centre of US trade policy.
Speaking at a White House press conference, he promised to build on the
North American Free Trade Agreement between the US, Canada and Mexico by
expanding it to include free-market democracies such as Argentina and Chile.
The president, who has been fighting an uphill battle to win Congress
approval for Nafta, predicted that the House of Representatives would give
its backing in its deciding vote next week. 'I honestly believe we're going
to win it now,' he said.
Mr Clinton said he did not want to exaggerate the potential job gains to be
derived from Nafta alone, although he believed it was clear it would create
more jobs than it lost.
Much greater opportunities would come, however, when the pact could be
expanded to other market-oriented economies and with the successful
conclusion of the Uruguay Round of negotiations on the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade.
'The real job growth . . . will come when all the other Latin American
democracies and free-market economies also join in a great trade group with
Mexico, Canada and the US.
'And it will come because, once this happens, we will have enormously
increased influence in the world community to argue that we ought to adopt a
worldwide trade agreement before the end of the year,' he added.
After Tuesday night's Nafta debate between vice-president Al Gore and Mr
Ross Perot, the former independent presidential candidate, Mr Clinton sought
to portray next week's Congress vote as critical for the US's ability to
negotiate freer trade opportunities from its partners not only in Latin
America but also in the Uruguay Round.
Mr Gore warned in the debate that a defeat for Nafta would make conclusion
of the Gatt round difficult.
An expansion of Nafta to include the rest of Latin America was promised by
Mr Clinton's predecessor, Mr George Bush. But little has been heard of such
talk in recent months as the prospects of Congress accepting free trade even
with neighbouring Mexico seemed so remote.
Mexican stocks soared 81.49 points to a record close at 2,035.33, and the
peso recovered because of optimism over the result of the Gore-Perot debate.
