<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Clinton pledges trade initiatives: Approval of Nafta hailed
as boost for Gatt talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A JUBILANT US president Bill Clinton arrived in Seattle for his Asian summit
yesterday on the wings of a famous victory in Congress, and promising new
initiatives to liberalise world trade.
His mission, he said, was to drive down world trade barriers as a spur to US
economic revival.
Earlier, Mr Clinton declared from the White House lawn that the House of
Representatives' approval of the North American Free Trade Agreement was 'a
long step in the right direction' of more open markets and more vigorous
international competition.
The Nafta vote gave the US 'the economic, political and moral standing' to
make its case, he said, not only with the leaders of the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation group but also in the push for a successful conclusion
to the Uruguay Round of global trade talks.
Mr Clinton's optimism was echoed by trade officials in Europe who said the
Nafta vote had improved the chances of an agreement on trade liberalisation
measures under the Geneva-based General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade by
the December 15 deadline.
Mr Peter Sutherland, director general of Gatt, said: 'There is no negotiator
in Geneva today who isn't breathing a sigh of relief as a result of the
vote.'
The Nafta debate had cast a shadow over Gatt talks for several weeks, tying
US negotiators' hands even though time was perilously short. It is now hoped
that talks next week in Washington between Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade
representative, and Sir Leon Brittan, EC commissioner, will give
long-awaited impetus to the negotiations.
The US Senate is expected to approve Nafta next week, as is its Mexican
counterpart. Mr Clinton said President Salinas had invited US vice-president
Al Gore for the Mexican side of the ratification process. The new trading
bloc, which includes Canada, is to take effect on January 1.
The House victory, on a vote of 234-200, was far more comfortable than had
appeared likely even as the House debated the agreement. The majority was
composed of 132 of the 175 Republicans and 102 of the 258 Democrats, with
the sole independent voting against.
Yesterday, Mr Clinton thanked all who had voted in favour of Nafta and hoped
that the bipartisan spirit that had carried the day could be applied to
other great issues facing the US, such as healthcare reform.
The president also went to great lengths to compliment the opposition and to
heal the open wounds in his especially with organised labour.
Trade union leaders remained unmollified. The full hierarchy of the AFL-CIO,
the umbrella union organisation, held a press conference to express regret
at Nafta's passage. Mr Bill Bywater, head of the electricians, warned those
Democrats who voted in favour: 'We're going to make sure we get even at the
polls.' Mr Owen Bieber, of the car workers, said Senate votes next week
would be duly noticed, too.
Mr Ross Perot, a loser in the Nafta debate, also threatened retaliation by
his independent movement.
US stocks fell after investors took the Nafta vote as a signal to take
profits. The Dow closed off 19.01 points at 3,685.34.
In Geneva, Mr Sutherland, at a briefing to underline trade liberalising
moves that have already been provisionally agreed, warned of difficulties
ahead. He said: 'The overall picture is heartening, but there are still
significant difficulties in bringing the round to a conclusion.'
In Brussels, Sir Leon said the vote would remove a big distraction for the
US and allow a final drive for a Gatt agreement.
