<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Nafta vote hailed as boost for Gatt: 'A long step in the
right direction,' says Clinton
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TRADE officials said yesterday that US congressional approval of the North
American Free Trade Agreement should be used to secure a successful
completion of the Uruguay Round of trade liberalisation talks.
Mr Peter Sutherland, director general of the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade, praised President Bill Clinton's success, but was quick to note
that the vote in the House of Representatives on Wednesday night, by 234 to
200, was 'just half of the battle won'.
He said: 'Half the battle because Nafta and similar enterprises - no less
the European Union - cannot themselves thrive in isolation. They are not
economically self-sustainable and must be part of a broader world trading
system under the aegis of the Gatt.
'The other half of the battle, making the Nafta a genuine positive force in
the world economy, must be the conclusion of the Uruguay Round.'
Trade negotiators in Geneva have set a December 15 deadline for completion
of the round. The Nafta vote had cast a shadow over Gatt talks for several
weeks, tying US negotiators' hands when the time remaining for completing
the round has been perilously short.
Amid rising optimism that long-elusive trade-liberalising measures are
finally within negotiators' grasp, expectations have run high that the
success of the Nafta vote would allow top US and EU trade negotiators
meeting in Washington early next week to provide long-awaited impetus.
Mr Clinton, before flying to his Asian summit in Seattle, said the House
approval of Nafta was 'a long step in the right direction' of more open
markets and more vigorous international competition.
The vote gave the US 'the economic, political and moral standing' to make
its case with the Asian leaders and in the final push to conclude the
Uruguay Round.
The measure was passed by a far more comfortable margin than had appeared
likely even as the House debated the agreement.
Mr Sutherland's comments came during a Geneva briefing intended to underline
trade liberalising moves that have already been provisionally agreed, and to
focus on what is at risk if the few outstanding differences result in
failure.
'What is in the bank is still capable of being lost,' he said. 'The overall
picture is heartening, but there are still significant difficulties in
bringing the round to a conclusion.
'There is a lot there that should stimulate the participants with the
knowledge of how much they stand to lose.'
In Brussels, Sir Leon Brittan, EU trade commissioner, also warmly welcomed
the House vote, saying it would remove a big distraction for the Clinton
administration and allow a final drive for agreement in the Gatt talks.
However, Sir Leon sounded one note of caution, telling reporters that he
needed to look at the 'small print' to see what the White House may have
offered members of Congress to get their vote and how it might affect Gatt.
With only four weeks remaining to deadline for a Gatt deal, Sir Leon is due
to hold talks with Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, in Washington
next week.
A measure of concern exists that so much remains to be negotiated in the
Gatt talks, with so little time remaining. 'You have a feeling that each
side has spent half of its time calculating how to blame the other in the
event of a failure,' one Commission official said.
